<DOC><DOCNO> AP880709-0051 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-88 0645EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Burma     07-09 0147</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Burma,0151</SECOND><HEAD>Authorities Lift Curfew Imposed After Riots</HEAD><DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Authorities today lifted a dusk-to-dawncurfew that was imposed in Rangoon after thousands of studentsrioted in the streets on June 21, state radio said.   A ban on public gatherings also was lifted, the broadcast said.   According to the government, six policemen and three civilianswere killed in the rioting. The violence erupted after universitystudents pressed demands, including release of colleagues detainedin earlier protests, and the government responded by closing theschools.   The government said that on Thursday and Friday, it freed all784 people detained in connection with last month's riots and otherrioting in March. Of those, 288 were students, it said.   The government also for the first time made a concession tostudent demands, announcing on Friday that students expelled fromschools for the March-June demonstrations will be readmitted.</TEXT></DOC>